<p>Though Payton was unaware of it, <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/rackauckas-689306-jacobs-letter.html" target="_blank" title="Escalera was a jailhouse informant who would turn from cellblock friend to star witness">Escalera was a jailhouse informant who would turn from cellblock friend to star witness</a> in the penalty portion of Payton&rsquo;s 1982 trial. His testimony about Payton&rsquo;s &ldquo;severe problem&rdquo; with women and sex helped put Payton on death row 33 years ago for one of the most vicious crimes of the era.</p>
<p>Now the old case looms as a battleground again, another in a spate of resolved cases that have drawn new scrutiny due to <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/informants-693296-attorney-dekraai.html" target="_blank" title="Orange County&rsquo;s ongoing jailhouse-informant controversy">Orange County&rsquo;s ongoing jailhouse-informant controversy</a>. The issue is whether prosecutors followed the law in disclosing evidence that they must make available to defense attorneys to assure a fair trial.</p>
<p>For Payton, now 61, the question is of mounting urgency. He is high on the list of condemned felons in California &ndash; and the next in line from Orange County &ndash; eligible to receive a lethal injection. Nine years after the last convicted killer was put to death here, <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/death-691941-state-court.html" target="_blank" title="state officials this month unveiled a new, single-drug protocol">state officials this month unveiled a new, single-drug protocol</a> that could result in executions resuming as soon as next year.</p>
<p>&ldquo;For almost two decades, we have alleged and the state has denied that Deputy District Attorney Michael Jacobs unlawfully concealed information that was favorable to Mr. Payton&rsquo;s defense in order to secure his conviction and death sentence,&rdquo; Payton&rsquo;s habeas corpus attorney, Margo Rocconi, said last week. Even now, with Orange County informant issues spawning national news and law enforcement <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/attorney-693017-office-district.html" target="_blank" title="officials scrambling to contain the damage">officials scrambling to contain the damage</a> and adopt reforms, Rocconi said, the District Attorney&rsquo;s Office continues to balk at turning over certain informant records as part of the legal discovery process.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Over the past five months, we have repeatedly asked the Orange County District Attorney&rsquo;s Office for discovery regarding the informants in Mr. Payton&rsquo;s case,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;but they have produced nothing.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Susan Kang Schroeder, chief of staff for District Attorney Tony Rackauckas, disputed Rocconi&rsquo;s accusations, saying prosecutors will give Payton&rsquo;s legal team everything they are obligated to turn over.</p>
<p>Former prosecutor Jacobs, now a private attorney, responded that he followed the law and was vindicated in appellate court.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I never willfully withheld any evidence in the Payton matter,&rdquo; Jacobs said Sunday. &ldquo;That was adjudicated in a federal writ of habeas 16 years ago. If she wants to relitigate it again, she may try,&rdquo; he said about Rocconi, &ldquo;but Payton has already exhausted his state and federal remedies.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The fight over informant records has been central to two high-profile death penalty cases awaiting trial in Orange County. One involves Scott Dekraai, <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/dekraai-612380-salon-shot.html" target="_blank" title="who confessed to gunning down eight people at a Seal Beach beauty salon in 2011">who confessed to gunning down eight people at a Seal Beach beauty salon in 2011</a> &ndash; the worst mass homicide in the county&rsquo;s history. The other is the case against Daniel Wozniak, <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/herr-356467-wozniak-grand.html" target="_blank" title="a community theater actor accused of shooting two people">a community theater actor accused of shooting two people</a> in Los Alamitos and Costa Mesa in 2010 and beheading one of them.</p>
<p>Assistant Public Defender Scott Sanders, who represents both men, <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/sanders-684780-attorney-case.html" target="_blank" title="touched off the informant scandal by digging into how so-called jailhouse snitches are used">touched off the informant scandal by digging into how so-called jailhouse snitches are used</a> and tracked by prosecutors and the Sheriff&rsquo;s Department, which operates the jail system. A series of hearings on the issue ended with a judge ousting the district attorney from prosecuting Dekraai&rsquo;s penalty-phase trial, a decision that has been appealed by the state Attorney General&rsquo;s Office.</p>
<p>Sanders, however, <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/wozniak-689424-informants-sanders.html" target="_blank" title="lost his battle to remove local prosecutors from the Wozniak case">lost his battle to remove local prosecutors from the Wozniak case</a>, which is headed to trial in early December.</p>
<p>Local prosecutors have conceded unintentional mistakes in the Dekraai case, but say the defense attorney&rsquo;s broader misconduct accusations are reckless and wrong.</p>
<p>In a 752-page legal motion filed in August in the Wozniak case, Sanders cited the Payton death penalty conviction and the two informants involved as an example of what he called a &ldquo;bottomless well of jailhouse informant concealment&rdquo; by Orange County authorities dating back more than 30 years.</p>
<p>Sanders contends that the complete story about the informants&rsquo; backgrounds and their close relationship with prosecutors never got to Payton or his defense team and therefore never was told to the jury. Those circumstances and a &ldquo;low-energy defense&rdquo; provided by Payton&rsquo;s original attorney resulted in what Sanders&rsquo; legal motion describes as &ldquo;an utter disaster for due process, in a case that has been playing out since Ronald Reagan was president.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Payton was convicted of exceptionally brutal crimes. Physical evidence and eye-witness testimony tied him to the rape and murder of Pamela Montgomery, a 21-year-old woman stabbed a dozen times at a home in Garden Grove. Payton also was convicted of trying to murder two others who were present in the hours before dawn in May 1980: Patricia Pensinger, who survived 40 stab wounds, and Pensinger&rsquo;s 10-year-old son, Blaine, who was stabbed 23 times but lived.</p>
<p>The key question from the outset was whether Payton would be sentenced to death. Escalera&rsquo;s testimony, coupled with the heinous nature of the crime and testimony from other witnesses, including one of Payton&rsquo;s ex-girlfriends, prevailed over the defense&rsquo;s argument that Payton&rsquo;s life should be spared because of his religious transformation, according to a case summary prepared by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Escalera testified regarding his jailhouse conversations with Payton,&rdquo; the court noted in 2001, in rejecting one of Payton&rsquo;s appeals. &ldquo;In addition, Patricia Stone, Payton&rsquo;s former girlfriend, testified that she had once been awakened with Payton holding a kitchen knife to her neck. He began stabbing her chest and arms.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The defense presented eight witnesses, including Payton&rsquo;s pastor, a deputy sheriff, four inmates, his mother, and the director of a religious organization that ministered to prisoners. They testified that Payton had made a sincere commitment to God, had a calming effect on other prisoners, and could help others while in prison through Bible study classes and a prison ministry.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Five years after that appeal &ndash; and nearly a quarter-century after Payton&rsquo;s trial &ndash; Escalera signed a handwritten declaration in which he finally laid out the full scope of his work for law enforcement.</p>
<p>The 2006 declaration, obtained by the Register, indicated that he was not just any other cellmate. Besides being an informant for the Orange County Sheriff&rsquo;s Department and District Attorney&rsquo;s Office, Escalera also worked as an informant for the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration, the FBI and the Los Angeles County Sheriff&rsquo;s Department.</p>
<p>The Fullerton Police Department considered him so vital to its drug-enforcement operations that detectives provided Escalera with an apartment he used while out of jail, in addition to giving him free food stamps, according to the declaration.</p>
<p>From 1977 to 1982, Escalera wrote, &ldquo;I considered myself to be working as a government agent at all times.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Escalera also said in his signed statement that he expected &ndash; and was later given &ndash; leniency for felony charges against him, including a 1981 armed robbery, in exchange for his informant testimony. &ldquo;I knew from having testified in three cases before Bill&rsquo;s that there is an unwritten rule that I would receive consideration for my pending sentences ... and I did,&rdquo; Escalera wrote.</p>
<p>Payton&rsquo;s new attorney, Rocconi, has obtained the declarations, but she still wants prosecutors to turn over Escalera&rsquo;s Criminal Informant Index card, or CII, which could indicate, for example, whether Escalera was considered a reliable informant.</p>
<p>Although Payton has exhausted his death-penalty appeals, Rocconi said she may seek to reopen the case and is weighing legal action against the District Attorney&rsquo;s Office for failing to make full disclosures.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The Orange County District Attorney&rsquo;s Office should not be in the business of concealing evidence or winning at all costs,&rdquo; Rocconi said. &ldquo;The mission statement of the Orange County District Attorney&rsquo;s Office is to enforce the law in a just, honest, efficient and ethical manner.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Rewarding informants for their help is legal, but one of the judgments that prosecutors must make is whether giving an informant leniency &ndash; usually by forgiving crimes or reducing jail time &ndash; accomplishes enough to justify rewarding or sometimes releasing a known or suspected bad actor back on the streets, said Alexandra Natapoff, a Loyola Law School professor who has testified before Congress on the issue and wrote the book &ldquo;Snitching: Criminal Informants and the Erosion of American Justice.&rdquo;</p>
<p>In the case of Escalera, the trade-off would prove disastrous to a gas station attendant and his family.</p>
<p>Facing a felony charge for robbing and beating another man in a hotel room, Escalera might have spent years in prison, but former county prosecutor Jacobs and others signed off on a plea arrangement allowing Escalera to receive probation, according to the state Attorney General&rsquo;s Office. Jacobs has acknowledged signing the plea agreement.</p>
<p>Escalera, already released on his own recognizance, was allowed to remain free when the case ended &ndash; but only temporarily. A few months later, he got into a wee-hour altercation at a gas station, drew a gun and fatally shot station attendant Edward Rios in the neck, according to Los Angeles County Superior Court records.</p>
<p>The star informant had become a killer.</p>
<p>Said Jacobs: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a prosecutor&rsquo;s worst nightmare.&rdquo;</p>
